<subSubSection pageId="148" pageNumber="149" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="148.[151,1436,151,464]" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,332,356]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="148" pageNumber="149" reason="1">Remarks.</emphasis>
Fishermen call this species the &quot;pelagic red crab&quot; or &quot;tuna crab.” Usually, it occurs off the coast of 
<collectingRegion box="[151,325,367,391]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Baja California</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[336,421,367,391]" name="Mexico" pageId="148" pageNumber="149">Mexico</collectingCountry>
but can be carried northward during years of warm currents. The crabs may be stranded in tide pools and on the beach. Numerous pelagic fishes, dolphins and the humpback whale eat these crabs. Hendrickx &amp; Harvey (1998) provided an extensive list of references.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
